  "response": "We want to simplify the expression $\\frac{x-\\frac{1}{x}}{1+\\frac{1}{x}}$ where it is defined. The expression is defined when $x \\neq 0$ and $1+\\frac{1}{x} \\neq 0$, which means $x \\neq -1$.\n\nWe can multiply the numerator and denominator by $x$ to get rid of the fractions within the fraction:\n$$\\frac{x-\\frac{1}{x}}{1+\\frac{1}{x}} = \\frac{x\\left(x-\\frac{1}{x}\\right)}{x\\left(1+\\frac{1}{x}\\right)} = \\frac{x^2-1}{x+1}.$$\nThen we can factor the numerator as a difference of squares:\n$$\\frac{x^2-1}{x+1} = \\frac{(x-1)(x+1)}{x+1}.$$\nSince $x \\neq -1$, we have $x+1 \\neq 0$, so we can cancel the factor of $x+1$ in the numerator and denominator:\n$$\\frac{(x-1)(x+1)}{x+1} = x-1.$$\nTherefore, the simplified expression is $x-1$, where $x \\neq 0$ and $x \\neq -1$.\n\nFinal Answer: The final answer is $\\boxed{x-1}$",
